ghprop_problem: This past week I strained my back.  That area is fine but now it has progressed to my hip and SI region and has been worsening over the past couple of days.
ghprop_bother: I am unable to golf or garden. I am supposed to play in 3 golf leagues this summer.  I also like to walk and hike which I am currently unable to do.  It is painful when I weight bear on my left left especially when I start to walk after sitting.
ghprop_relieve: I have been taking Advil/ Tylenol  ( which I rarely take) and icing it.  I am trying gentle stretches.  I am limiting walking etc and have taken a break from golf.  I supervised my husband on where to plant my plants.  My friend is a retired chiropractor and I plan on seeing him today.
ghprop_problem_2: I have poor memory recall--especially with names, the name of the book I am reading etc.  I start to tell a story and then stop because I can't come up with a word.
ghprop_bother_2: Mostly frustrating and embarrassing .
ghprop_relieve_2: I am definitely a note taker- my notes have notes.  In my small group of friends we say the word " chandelier" when we can't come up with a word.  We laugh it off and everyone jokes how they can't remember things- but it's not always funny.
psprop_problem: I have a 93 yo mother in the nursing home who has started to fail. She will be 94 this August.  Her mother died on her 94th birthday.   I am able to visit her for 3 meals a week for two hours to encourage her to eat.  I am fortunate that after COVID I have been one of the few that have gotten to have compassionate care visits.  Though I enjoy our visits ,it  is also a reminder to see that my mother is aging and has lost weight.   I am very sentimental.
psprop_bother: I wouldn't trade visiting by mother for anything but it is time consuming- 3 hours a day , 3 times a week.
psprop_relieve: Nothing - Be grateful for each day we can visit and share another dessert together.
psprop_problem_2: My husband with recently diagnosed with Parkinson' s  Disease.   This is very much a fear of the unknown - what will his PD path look like,  how many " good years" will he have left.  He know feels he is "different " from all of his friends.
psprop_bother_2: Mostly it saddens me.  At this time, physically he is active and can do everything he wants to.  I am afraid of what  his physical/ mental  state will be and how he/we will handle it.  It is more of a reminder of our immortality.  We are trying to exercise and stay active together and this is helpful with PD.
psprop_relieve_2: My spouse and I talk about it-  what it's like to have PD.   We are involved in a local  PD support group.
psprop_problem_3: My younger sister was diagnosed with breast cancer and is currently undergoing chemotherapy and has finished her radiation.
psprop_bother_3: We spend much more  time talking on the phone.  Though it take up time in my day,  it has made us closer.   I send her articles on diet and stress relief that I think might help her
psprop_relieve_3: I feel better when I talk to her and finally got to see her for the first time  after COVID last week.

ghprop_problem: Parkinson's...specifically Tremors or bradykinesia.  I can't say which is most bothersome.
ghprop_bother: Tremors and bradykinesia affect the ability to do computer work and my job.  They also impact the ability to workout, to drink and eat, to quilt,...  Some days are fine, other days not.
ghprop_relieve: I take a break from whatever I am doing.  Sometimes I'll rest or do/listen to a mindfulness/meditation video.  Started Sinemet in Aug.
ghprop_problem_2: Asthma
ghprop_bother_2: It is hard to breathe or catch my breath sometimes.
ghprop_relieve_2: I use a daily inhaler, and use a rescue inhaler  before an intense workout (or during if I forgot to use it before class).  Also, some of my Power for Parkinson's classes work on breathing.
ghprop_problem_3: Insomnia or not wanting to go to sleep.
ghprop_bother_3: It is hard to get up in the morning, and sometimes I need a nap during the day.
ghprop_relieve_3: I try to take Gabapentin and now Melatonin earlier at night to help make me sleepy, and try to get the room at a comfortable temperature for sleeping.
psprop_problem: I am not sure if I should be retiring early to enjoy life before PD symptoms really take hold, if I have the funds to safely do that, if I even WANT to do that.
psprop_bother: Work can sometimes be stressful, and when I am stressed, tremors can be worse.
psprop_relieve: Nothing other than running the pros and cons of the decision in my head.
pdprop_problem: Tremors or Bradykinesia
pdprop_bother: Tremors and Bradykinesia can both affect the ability to work at a computer, to eat and drink, to quilt, to pour a glass of water, to sometimes operate the phone or text.
pdprop_relieve: I try to relax, go lie down for a bit, take a Mindfulness/Meditation class,...
pdprop_problem_2: Dystonia in right foot
pdprop_bother_2: So far, my only complaint is that it is uncomfortable - a cramp that doesn't go away.

ghprop_problem: The "off" periods in PD
ghprop_bother: Life is very unpredictable. I never know if the medicine is going to make it the full 3 hours. Being "off" is not fun- many of the symptoms return and it can be very difdficult to cope.
ghprop_relieve: If I feel myself going "off" I might take my medicine early. This has the effect of my ending up with a longer "off" period at the end of teh day.
ghprop_problem_2: Digestive system problems - constipation, acid reflux, and upset stomach are common for me.
ghprop_bother_2: These issues are generally uncomfortable and sometimes down right painful.
ghprop_relieve_2: Not much I can do about it. I am already using several anti-constipation aids - fiber, colace, MirLax, etc.
ghprop_problem_3: Balance - I frequently lose my balanceand have fallen on a couple of occasions.
ghprop_bother_3: I don't feel comfortable being active if I think I am going to fall. It can be very painful.
ghprop_relieve_3: Try to focus on my walking, slow down, and practice actions that will  helo prevent falls
psprop_problem: The interference of Covid-19 on my social  life.
psprop_bother: It is bothersome to have to re-think  everything we do and make a decision as to whether it is "safe" enough.   The political nature of the virus has the country even more divided.
psprop_relieve: I try to reman optimistic, yet reasonable  about what I can expect.
pdprop_problem: Off periods
pdprop_bother: unpredictability
pdprop_relieve: Try to adjust the timing of my medicine
pdprop_problem_2: Digestive issues
pdprop_bother_2: Generally uncomfortable/painful
pdprop_relieve_2: Use aides such as colace, fiber, myrlax, etc.
pdprop_bother_3: It hurts to fall so I am much more timid about doing some things
pdprop_relieve_3: Slow down, focus, practice not losing my balance

ghprop_problem: Abdominal pain due to ulcerative colitis.
ghprop_bother: It doesn't always affect my daily functioning, but it is painful, interrupts my work and free time, and it makes me feel weak and tired. Sometimes it prevents me from exercising. I have also experienced a link between inflammation and mood, so sometimes it affects my mood.
ghprop_relieve: I take multiple medications and supplements, including infusions every 7 weeks. I adhere to a strict diet in an attempt to avoid symptoms. I spend lots of money on medical care and mental health care. I frequently communicate with my doctors.
ghprop_problem_2: Inflammation in my gut due to ulcerative colitis.
ghprop_bother_2: It effects the way I eat. I adhere to a strict diet in an attempt to reduce inflammation. Inflammation causes my weight to go up and down, which is hard on my mental health. It affects my social life and how I'm able to participate. I'm usually not able to share the same meal with everyone at a party because of my anti-inflammation diet. And sometimes the inflammation causes abdominal pain and has other mental health effects.
ghprop_relieve_2: I take multiple medications and supplements, including infusions every 7 weeks. I adhere to a strict diet in an attempt to avoid symptoms. I spend lots of money on medical care and mental health care. I frequently communicate with my doctors.
psprop_problem: Anxiety and intense emotions.
psprop_bother: Sometimes it makes me feel exhausted. Sometimes it causes me to ruminate and have obsessive thoughts, trying to solve whatever problem I'm working through.
psprop_relieve: I take a medication to help. I see a therapist. I do yoga. I use a guided meditation app. I try to get enough sleep. I talk to friends and family. I monitor my menstrual cycle to be prepared for when emotions may come up.

ghprop_problem: Parkinson Disease and its myriad of symptoms that vary in severity throughout the day and night. Pain from constant toe curling, tremors, anxiety, constipation, gait, NOH, apathy, difficulty concentrating, having to take so many medications, poor sleep, and still trying to be an optimist.
ghprop_bother: I tire more quickly and don't feel I can accomplish things that used to be easy. I even have to concentrate to walk up the stairs.
ghprop_relieve: Walk my dog daily and try to take all my meds on a schedule on time. Diet and exercise and stretching frequently.
ghprop_problem_2: Temperature regulation. Easy to over-heat and yet most of the time my fingers and feet are cold to the point of annoying discomfort.
ghprop_bother_2: Spring, Summer, Fall - walk the dog and break a sweat.  Fall, Winter, Spring - walk the dog (wearing gloves even) and fingers hurt from cold.  Mow the lawn - need a shower / dry shirt.
ghprop_relieve_2: Rehydrate.  Wear Gloves.  Wear Socks to bed.
ghprop_problem_3: Eyesight and dry eyes getting worse.
ghprop_bother_3: Need reading glasses in increasing strength. Have to carry them with me all the time now.
ghprop_relieve_3: Own multiple pairs scattered throughout the house and cars.  Nightly eye drops to lesson pressure in eyes.
ghprop_problem_4: Poor dental health. Despite hygiene I have had majority of teeth needing caps, including wisdom teeth. Parkinson seems to have increased the frequency that I bite inner lips while chewing.
ghprop_bother_4: Expense of dentistry and the pain / fear of another hole within my mouth / lips.
ghprop_relieve_4: Chew carefully smaller bites.  Floss.
ghprop_problem_5: Urinary urgency seems to be increasing.
ghprop_bother_5: Interrupts activities and is uncomfortable until relieved. Interferes with sleep also.
psprop_problem: Feeling inadequate. Daughter estranged. Son rarely communicates. Happily remarried. (but spouse finally regained sobriety after year of blackout drunks.) Family of origin still strong and supportive, but parents in advanced years with their own health risks.
psprop_bother: Stresses my own struggles with apathy.  Tempting to avoid versus face stressors yet past counseling experience has shown the folly of that path.
psprop_relieve: Exercise and meditation (i.e. I go hand pull weeds in the garden or yard to clear my mind.)
psprop_problem_2: I worry about my finances and how it will affect my spouse in the long run.
psprop_bother_2: Feeling helpless and fearful of the political aspects of our country. Interferes with motivation to participate in life.
psprop_relieve_2: Reduced watching news. Pray more.
psprop_problem_3: Losing overall strength. (beyond just getting older.)
psprop_bother_3: Hips hurt after sitting for periods of time.
psprop_relieve_3: Not enough.  Stretching before I walk after standing.  Be grateful I can walk.
pdprop_problem: Knowing that it will most likely keep getting worse.
pdprop_bother: Every time I encounter an issue that is new or increased in difficulty it feels like another loss to my being. Slowly dying instead of living.
pdprop_relieve: Smile!!! It's easier to be happy than sad.  (p.s. I fear the PD mask as it creeps into my life.)
pdprop_problem_2: Constipation. Losing muscle control to produce a bowel movement.
pdprop_bother_2: Internal discomfort and impact on GI tract to absorb medications with regularity affected.
pdprop_relieve_2: Probiotics, diet, hydration, walking, stool softeners.
pdprop_bother_3: Pattern of weather (pressure dropping) seems to make it harder to think " molasses brain " effect.
pdprop_relieve_3: Treat them as Parky days and stop feeling guilty about parking on the couch.
pdprop_bother_4: Runny nose when below 40 degrees F.
pdprop_relieve_4: There's Snot much I can do.
pdprop_bother_5: Can't tell if the milk has spoiled.
pdprop_relieve_5: Ask my spouse to check it for me before pouring it on my cereal.

ghprop_problem: Parkinson Disease (PD) Has made me tired, feel exhausted most of the time and the more tired I get the worse the memory gets, the tremors get, the back hunches me over, stiffness, don't talk loud enough, don't taste stuff, and can't disguise when I have good hand at cards or don't like what someone says, tremor goes wild.
ghprop_bother: PD has resticted my abilities, stanium to keep up with our yard, go fishing, hunting, hiking, gardening.  Fix things.  Playing games
ghprop_relieve: Taking 1 Sinemet every 2 hours, 7 or 8 a day and Sinemet ER at night. Taking strengthening, balance, boxing classes at Wellness 360.  Switch to battery operated tools for the yard and garden.  Rest my back for a 1/2 hour to and hour with a small pillow under my back.  Went on Amantadine 3 weeks ago for tremors
ghprop_problem_2: Frequent urination and leakage.  Grandfather, Father, and cousin had prostrate cancer.
ghprop_bother_2: Up and down to go, interrupt nights sleep, afraid to go places.  In the warm tend not to drink enough probably a 2, cold weather accidents, and more frequent so would be a 3
ghprop_relieve_2: Cut back on drinking water, caffeine, tomatoes,   Wear pullups in cold weather.  Plan trips.  See a urologists' every year for tests.
ghprop_problem_3: My back it seems like one problem after another.  Latest is a bulge between T12 and L1.
ghprop_bother_3: Makes it tough to sit and concentrat when sitting.
ghprop_relieve_3: Rest my back for a 1/2 hour to and hour with a small pillow under my back in bed.
ghprop_problem_4: Depression, should have listed as part of PD but was diagnosed with it long before PD or should that make it 1st.  Seems like things go OK the they don't, hard to describe.
ghprop_bother_4: When my mind says push an exercise something says why bother.
ghprop_relieve_4: Take 40mg Fluoxetine daily.  Do things like this to hopefully help others.
ghprop_problem_5: When diagnosed with something like PD.  There tends to be tendency for frequent unration and back pain to referred back to neurologist and vice versa.
ghprop_bother_5: May live with a problem I don't have to or waste time in the wrong office.
psprop_problem: Every thing takes longer.
psprop_bother: My mind still thinks an 10 min to get ready to but can take that long to button a shirt.
psprop_relieve: Plan
psprop_problem_2: Dog won't sleep
psprop_bother_2: Not sure if its the PD or lack of sleep.
psprop_relieve_2: Go bed early, take over for the wife
psprop_problem_3: Should have seen a marriage consular years ago.
psprop_relieve_3: Went a consoler back when diagnosed with PD, invited wife, won't go.  Nothing now.
pdprop_problem: Concerned about making the PD worse.  Have  a theory  that a fall ice skating where my feet went out from under me forward hitting the back of my head on ice may have started it 2011.
pdprop_bother: Try to be more careful
pdprop_relieve: Try to eat right, combination brain and Mediterranean diet, get exercise,  don't ice skate
pdprop_problem_2: Tremors right side of body.  Mostly right arm and hand.

pdprop_relieve_2: Tried mindfulness with limited success.  3rd week of trying Amantadine seems to have lessened the amplitude.
pdprop_problem_3: How tired I am, the example of metal jacket they had at a moving day sums it up, feel your taking everything you own with you..

pdprop_relieve_3: Exercise, stretch at levels a little harder each time.

pdprop_relieve_4: Walk with arms behind my back.

ghprop_problem: Currently it is cognitive fatigue. I have a difficult time staying focused on anything for any real length of time. My brain seems to just get overloaded and shut down. I often have to take naps after balancing my check book or driving for more than 1hr, or doing any other tasks that take a lot of cognitive focus.
ghprop_bother: I can not get done as much as I would like too. I'm either having to take frequent breaks or taking naps. It is frustrating because they are things I used to have no problem at all doing. I also can't block out things either to stay focused. I can't type or read anything if there is a tv or radio on or if other people in the room are having a conversation. I used to be able to block those things out.
ghprop_relieve: I try to avoid doing things that take a lot of cognitive focus. If I have to do something I will try to take frequent breaks and move around in-between, or even just stop and do another project or task that needs to be done in the house that doesn't require much thought, like laundry or vacuuming or I will do some exercises for awhile.
ghprop_problem_2: Sleep disorders. I have a difficult time staying asleep and often when I wake up after just a few hours of sleep I am unable to fall back asleep. I also have very vivid dreams some times and wake up because I have punched or kicked something. Sometimes my dreams are vivid but not violent and when I wake it takes me a little while to determine if the dream really happened or if it was just a dream. I believe my tremors also contribute to waking in the middle of the night too. When I have insomnia and lie there for an hour or more I end up having the need to get up to use the bathroom.
ghprop_bother_2: I never feel fully rested, I almost always feel like I'm running on 1/4 full. I have not slept well consistently in 20 years. If I do sleep, my deep sleep or REM sleep is only a total of 1-3hrs per night and that time is broken up throughout the night with either awake time or light sleep time. I had a sleep study done on me about 8 years ago, 6years before my diagnosis and the study showed I was breathing fine but that I was waking out of REM sleep about every 3 minutes on average.
ghprop_relieve_2: I take qty 2 tablets of 50/200 Carbadopa Levadopa CR before bed. I also take 20mg of Melatonin, and I use CBD oil. I exercise regularly.
ghprop_problem_3: Dystonia, and cramping. I have dystonia in my feet where my toes often want to curl up, my feet off ache and will get cramps. Sometimes the ache goes up into my calves. I also have dystonia in my eyes making it sometimes difficult to keep them open when meds are off. I have dystonia in my neck and spine as well making it difficult to maintain posture and causing aches and pain in my neck and shoulders. My hands also cramp and ache transferring into my forearms.
ghprop_bother_3: The pain caused by this is very uncomfortable. It makes it hard to sit still and relax. Pain makes it hard to sleep well too. The cramping, pain and toes curling up will sometimes throw balance off too. Pain in my forearms is affected more when typing, writing etc.
ghprop_relieve_3: I use a massage ball about the size of a tenis ball and roll it under my feet if I'm sitting down. I frequently stretch my arms, neck, shoulders and feet. I go for massage therapy once a month and acupuncture once a month and include cupping for my neck back and shoulders. I also have found that CBD oil helps a little.
ghprop_problem_4: Tremors. I have primarily resting tremors in my right hand, right leg, left hand, jaw and sometimes left leg.
ghprop_bother_4: My body never feels at rest, something is always moving and muscles fighting against each other. In my right hand it is difficult get the tremors to stop enough to start writing at times, it also tremors when holding a fork or spoon some times. Forearms get achy because muscles are constantly twitching. I have to wear a mouth guard at night to prevent my teeth from clenching or grinding causing my jaw to be sore and have an under bite the next day.
ghprop_relieve_4: I get accupuncture and massages once a month each. I wear a mouth guard at night.
psprop_problem: The cognitive fatigue makes it difficult to get through the day. It drains me and and my mind and body both want to shut down. I get frustrated with myself at times because of the cognitive slowness and that I struggle doing things and it takes me significantly longer to do them than it used to. The cognitive fatigue also makes being in social atmosphere exhausting trying to filter out the other noises and distractions to have a conversation with one or more people.
psprop_bother: I have to limit or plan for times to spend with family and friends so that I can be rested and and my mind can be clear and prepared to deal with the extra cognitive fatigue. Also during these social times and trying to deal with the added noise and distractions my other symptoms like tremors and other motor symptoms also become worse.
psprop_relieve: I don't go out to restaurants as much with friends because the added noise is difficult to deal with, if I do I have to plan enough time to take a nap before hand. If during the time with friends or family it gets to be too much, I either go home early or sometimes will just step away and go outside to a quite location for awhile to try and ease my symptoms.
psprop_problem_2: Financially, I have had to stop working and go on disability. I have disability insurance through my previous employer but it is still a significant reduction in pay and I am stuck with that same fixed income now for about 20 years then I'll be on a fixed retirement income. When if I was working I'd be making more plus receiving raises over the next 20yrs and be able to put more money away for retirement. Also the amount of forms and paper work that needs to be filled out and read when going on disability is very confusing and causes a lot of cognitive fatigue and is very difficult to understand and get through. Also being limited on what retirement funds I can access and when is causing me to have to file for bankruptcy because I can no longer afford my bills on the reduced income and I can not access my money that I have in a profit sharing plan with the company I left until I am approved for social security disability.
psprop_bother_2: It causes extra stress trying to figure out how to afford things and what the future will be like for me. How and where will I live.
psprop_relieve_2: Nothing
pdprop_problem: The cognitive fatigue.
pdprop_bother: I've already stated this. It affects, social, family, and financial aspects of daily living. It also causes me to get frustrated with myself not being able to figure things out or do things the way I used to and causes me to have to take naps more often.
pdprop_relieve: Try to avoid it and take naps when necessary.

concerns: I am not sure what this question is referring to. If it is for the following two questions, The increased depression was a concern for me and I have since made a change in medications and doctors.
improve_format: Make Page 1 charts read like the rest of the report. With chart header and description top left and my score top right.  (fix typo in Anxiety scale description 3rd line last item is 4, should be 48)
onesuggestion: The last two items on the report sleep and cognitive, lower number is worse. Every other test higher number is worse. It would be nice to have these consistent
additional_feedback: For motor symptoms, I would like to see them broken down, and see how tremor, slowness, rigidity and whatever else is included in this separate. The reason is that one could have really bad tremors but be able to still move quickly without stiffness on first visit, have a change in meds or treatment and then have improved tremor control but worsened stiffness and/or increased slowness and the value could be the same. Knowing something got better but something else is worse would be helpful to me, to better speak with the neurologist about my treatment.     I also hoped to see results from the Mpower app, and Emerald and not just days completed. Again to know if tremors are better or worse, balance, gait, sleep etc. seeing this in a graph form with time vs measurement would be easy way to see trend, progression, med or treatment improvements.    Also I think the data will be very difficult to analyze and compare to find trends without having patients changes in medications or treatments such as DBS during the study phase noted.     The cognition report surprised me because I feel I struggle quite a bit from cognitive fatigue and I have difficulties balancing my check book and things of that nature that I could do easily before. I now often pick up my phone to do something or go to the kitchen and I don't know what I went there for or what I was looking at my phone for. Being in a testing situation is much easier to stay intent on details knowing you are going to be asked about specific items.     I think there should be more real world test for both motor and non motor symptoms, including vision, blood pressure, heart rate, individuals feeling of temperature, cold, hot, sweating, opening a jar and putting the top back on, opening/closing zip lock bags,
ghprop_problem: Currently my worst symptom has been dystonia. I have it in my neck, jaw, feet and hands
ghprop_bother: The pain from dystonia is very bothersome. Especially from my jaw and neck, it ends up causing severe headaches some days. The dystonia in my feet and hand is also uncomfortable. In my feet it has caused me to fall a few times because not only do my toes curl but my feet rotate in so I end up stepping down on the outside edge of my feet. My hands sometimes causes me to drop things or throw things without meaning too.
ghprop_relieve: I haven't found much to help except massage therapy and acupuncture offer some temporary relief usually only lasting a day or two.
ghprop_problem_2: Depression, lack of motivation. fatigue
ghprop_bother_2: It has been difficult to get the energy to do things I used to do, or to want to do things I used to enjoy. Many things around the house don't get done, my drive and ambition to exercise has been lost. I need to take naps sometimes a couple in one day.
ghprop_relieve_2: I take an SSRI but lately it has not been helping enough. The change seems to have been since my DBS surgery and reduction of Levadopa.
ghprop_bother_3: It affects my coordination. My left side seems slower than my right. Also my legs and arm coordination isn't their all the time.
ghprop_relieve_3: I've tried adjusting my DBS settings but still have not gotten rid of this feeling.
ghprop_problem_4: Interrupted Sleep, vivid dreams, acting out dreams, hearing noises that sound like voices, or music or my alarm upon waking and the noise is not real or is something different like the fan but I heard something different. Dreams sometimes seem real, that when I wake I don't know if it happened or not and sometimes I have to check if someone else is in my home with me or not. Sometimes it's difficult to fall back asleep after I wake up in the middle of the night.
ghprop_bother_4: I don't get quality sleep, which makes everything harder and worse during the day. I then have a
ghprop_relieve_4: I take melatonin before bed.
psprop_problem: Finances are always a concern, I'm on disability and live alone. Social events has been difficult due to Covid, I primarily stay at home.
psprop_bother: It adds to depression and makes being motivated to do anything more difficult.
psprop_relieve: Participate in Parkinson's zoom meetings, and watch webinars, work on projects around the home.
psprop_problem_2: Shopping in stores, primarily grocery stores.
psprop_bother_2: I have problems with space and no direction for shoppers so people are going in different directions, sensory overload, and it worsens my symptoms and sometimes I freeze for short time.
psprop_relieve_2: I use curb side pick up where available and order items online to avoid going to stores
pdprop_problem: Getting moving in the mornings.
pdprop_bother: I have to schedule 30min to 1hr just to get my body moving so I can get up and move enough to get out of bed some days. I'm stiff in the morning and need my medicine to kick in to be able to get going. I always used to hop right up when my alarm went of and got going.
pdprop_relieve: Have my morning meds by my bed with some water.

ghprop_problem: My depression and anxiety.  I think some is heredity and some is caused by my being a people pleaser, not liking conflict, not knowing how to properly express my feelings  with honesty at the time I need to express how I am feeling rather than letting them "fester" and making things worse later on.
ghprop_bother: I hold feelings in and get very quiet.  If I don't address what I'm feeling with the person it involves, I start what I call "stinking thinking", meaning I heap my faults together and start in a downward spiral that causes anxiety and depression.
ghprop_relieve: Sometimes I am able to write a letter to the person.  This is easier for me to put words on paper rather than having to think at the time and talk.  I feel "pressured into a corner" and need to step away from the situation so I can express my anger out loud, calm down and look at the situation with more perspective and/or rationally.  At other times I "rant" to another family member or friend.
ghprop_problem_2: I need physical activity each day for good mental health.  I need to feel/see that I have accomplished something during the day.  There are many tasks that need to be completed and I need to be able to work on something each day.
ghprop_bother_2: If I don't get to do a "job" or project that I have  on my "to do" list, I get frustrated and angry and take out these feelings on my spouse or those around me.
ghprop_relieve_2: Tell my spouse that I really need to do "this or that" first and then I will give you the attention you want. Or I get into doing a task without letting my spouse know .  I feel good about getting the task done.  However, my spouse gets upset with me for not letting her know.
psprop_problem: Not being able to work around the house or outside or do a project I want to work on because my spouse requires my attention or because I must do certain tasks because my spouse is disabled and cannot physically do a lot of the tasks that need to be done.
psprop_bother: I get frustrated, angry, moody, and/or have difficulty saying what I need to say or do for my well-being.  I need to not worry so much about somebody being angry with me or having a different idea about how to do an activity.
psprop_relieve: Sometimes nothing.  At other times just say "I need to do "this task" and then I'll to what the other person is requesting.

additional_feedback: Several of the results sections had my score placed within a range of possible results.  i.e. score ranges from 0 to 30, or 0 to 150, etc.  However, others give no range like that so it is difficult to place my score on the scale of possibilities.  For instance, the first one, Modified Movement Disorder, says "a higher score indicates more difficulties..."  I went from a "0" on one result to a "3" on another, but no indication of what the range is.   Similarly, the Depression scale.  It says that > or equal to 5 is a cut-off for screening of depression. ghprop_problem: Everything I did in my youth (teens & 20s) is now catching up to me in my 50s.  I never thought in a million years, I would have the aches and pains that I have now.
ghprop_bother: I am no longer capable of doing the things I used to do in a timely fashion due to my aching joints and back.  Everything has slowed to a crawl, and I don't like it
ghprop_relieve: Some days nothing, others, I bust butt to get things done.
psprop_problem: EXPECTATIONS!  They are driving me nuts.  I think I am a very caring/kind person, yet my sister tells me I am not empathic, my husband of 27/years is emotionally insecure and I want no relationship with his adult daughters.  They are mean/unforgiving people that I would steer clear of in a social situation.  Just because they are his blood, does not mean I have to love/like/or care about them.  His older sisters (2) could not be more different.  One is happy go lucky to the point of terrible decision making, the other, woe is me.
psprop_bother: I'm finding I that I am somewhat suffocated in all this "debbie-downer" emotional instability.
psprop_relieve: As for my sister, we had a "come to Jesus" argument a couple years ago, distancing ourselves from one another.  Over time, the relationship has come full circle.  As for my husband's sisters and the burr in my saddle, I have weekly coffee with my friend and unload.

ghprop_problem: I broke my back a couple years ago.  I worry that the vertebrae will break the other 50% severing my spinal cord. I do not want to live life paralyzed.
ghprop_bother: I'm a work horse and for me to have to slow down, or do nothing is mind blowing.  I love to be outside, and must admit my gardening takes a toll on my back, as does grooming my dogs, painting, sleeping.  What I used to do in 3-4 hours now takes all day, and with a day of rest in between.
ghprop_relieve: I've started to seek a holistic approach to my aches and pains.  I was being treated by Pain Management (no narcotics) for trigger point injections but decided to try something different.  I have accupuncture therapy twice a month, and so far, I am pleased with the response.
ghprop_problem_2: Mental/Grief.  I have anxiety/depression. Since loosing my agility K9 partner in August, my world is topsy turvy at best, and my heart is broken.  I have four other 4-legged kids at home, and I love them dearly, but Lilly was a gift!  2021 is the year for getting back on track with my whole person, and moving forward in a positive direction. I'm seeking counseling from a LCSW therapist to help me with life-long issues, as well as the loss of my beloved Champion.
ghprop_bother_2: My sleep pattern is disrupted, I can become withdrawn, and I have on numerous accounts had more than the 2-drink (alcohol) limit my husband and I have agreed to thus resulting in arguments, more anxiety, more depression.
ghprop_relieve_2: Alcoholism runs in my family.  Do I think I'm an alcoholic - no, but do I tend to go over board from time to time, yes.  My spouse does not drink, so I can see how it is no fun for him.  I've had one 4 oz glass of wine in the last 14-days.
psprop_problem: It's a rut, but a good rut.  I think sometimes I want to return to the workforce, but have become accustom to doing what I want and when, so I don't know if I could be a valued member a company team, certainly not full-time either.
psprop_bother: I try and do something/learn different things albeit gardening, for sure cooking, reading, and/or training my Golden Retriever.  While it may be boring to some, consistency in training is the key to success so it's not all that doom and gloom.
psprop_relieve: I keep at it, and try to shake it up every now and again.

ghprop_problem: Back pain
ghprop_bother: The back pain shows up after I have stood for 30-45 minutes, in the kitchen for example, doing household chores. The only thing that relieves it is sitting down, sometimes lying down.  Interestingly, it very seldom bothers me when walking (for exercise) or when playing pickleball.
ghprop_relieve: sit or lie down
ghprop_problem_2: Foot discomfort.  There is a feeling like an abrasion on the arch of my right foot.
ghprop_bother_2: I still do my daily activities, but I think that sometimes it affects my gait.
ghprop_relieve_2: Not much really...sometimes I put some type of "magic cream" on, like arnica or a magnesium  type. But, I have not found anything that really relieves it.
ghprop_problem_3: Muscle cramps in my lower extremities and feet.
ghprop_bother_3: The cramping usually shows up when I sit down and take my shoes off. Sometimes it seems to be near or right after I take my afternoon medication, though, quite honestly, I don't see any immediate relief after taking the meds. Also, at night when I go to bed, sometimes my feet will cramp...again after I take the weight off my feet.
ghprop_relieve_3: Stand up and put weight on my feet. Sometimes I put "magic cream" on the bottoms of my feet which sometimes seems to help. I also drink a glass of water with Calm mixed in before I go to bed.
ghprop_problem_4: chronic UTIs
ghprop_bother_4: impacts whole body including Parkinson's symptoms. Nobody seems to be able to help me with it.
ghprop_relieve_4: Try drinking more water, someone suggested D-mannose supplement. tried both powder and pills. Might help but I am not sure.
psprop_problem: I was diagnosed in February 2020. It is an anxiety-producing diagnosis.  I still have only told my family. I have not told my friends.  I am concerned that I will be treated "differently" once my friends know...maybe dismissed in some way.
psprop_bother: I am not sure that it affects my daily functioning. I think that I function pretty well. I am not sure how telling people about the diagnosis would help me.
psprop_relieve: Nothing at this point.
psprop_problem_2: I would say that some days I don't have the energy that I would like...I am not sure if the cause is age-related, physical or depression, or all three.
psprop_bother_2: On the days that I "don't do much", I worry about the fact that I "don't do much" and that it will affect the progress of the disease.
psprop_relieve_2: I try to walk every day and play pickleball as often as I can to keep the depression and the progression at bay...
pdprop_problem: Limited movement.
pdprop_bother: I think that on an overall PD scale that I probably move pretty well, but I notice the limitations when I fold laundry or go to something requiring finer motor skills. And, it varies from day to day. pdprop_relieve: I think that if I move more overall, ie. the walking or the pickleball or riding a bike, my overall movement improves.

ghprop_problem: Frequent UTI's.
ghprop_bother: When a UTI occurs, if it is not caught early, it effects my PD symptoms. I find that I am more fatigued, a little spacey, walking becomes a bit more awkward. Before this past summer, the UTI would present with very clear acute symptoms, ie burning, frequency, pressure. Howeever, this summer and fall, I have had two UTI's that have no acute symptoms, but, only vague fatigue, loss of energy and stamina...like I missed a medication dose. I can only determine what is going on by taking an at-home "culture" test. Then I treat it with antibiotics.
ghprop_relieve: I have seen alot of doctors, none of whom has found a solution. I take some supplements to support the urinary track ( primarily D-mannose). I tried vaginal laser treatments in the hopes of some residual help for the UTI's, but that does not seem to have worked.
ghprop_problem_2: Poor quality of sleep. In the past 3 months, I have been waking up at 1:30, 3:15, 4:30. It does not seem that it is a need to use the bathroom that causes me to wake up. Often I do not go right back to sleep. Most days I do not take a nap so am not sure of the cause of the interruptions.
ghprop_bother_2: I seem to run out of energy and focus in the afternoon.
ghprop_relieve_2: I take magnesium in the hopes that that will help. And, recently, have focused on drinking more water during the day. Maybe I am dehydrated???
psprop_problem: Not sure "bothered" is the correct word...I am concerned about staying as active as possible and as socially interactive.
psprop_bother: When I lose energy and motivation in the afternoon, I find that I am worried about it, but most days, don't do anything about it.

ghprop_problem: Pain, discomfort, and dyskinesia my right limb - from my fingers up to my shoulder. Sinemet will help lessen it, but definitely does not take it away. (The dyskinesia is limited to my fingers.
ghprop_bother: Keyboarding is difficult. I can do it, and do it, i.e; I have been working on genealogy on Ancestry.com and that is very doable, but composing long letters or transcriptions is definitely uncomfortable. I do more pointing and clicking now, and use the touch screen more often. Heat also bothers my arm. Gardening is harder, my arm becomes painful quicker, and if it is hot, and especially if it is humid, I become sick and weaker from the increasing discomfort.
ghprop_relieve: I have learned to garden early in the morning,  before it is hot, or to wait until another day. If it flares up while sitting, I will search for a comfortable position. Sometimes gripping something in my right hand helps. Sometimes resting it on a pillow helps. Sometimes when I finally find a good position, I don't want to move it. One time I had my husband bring me something because I didn't want to move. When I take my next Sinemet dose that will solve it, sometimes it takes awhile.
ghprop_problem_2: Fatigue. I don't have the stamina I used to have. I can't get as much done.
ghprop_bother_2: It takes me longer to do physical chores, housework, etc. I always feel behind
ghprop_relieve_2: Sometimes I just have to lie down, often for just 5-20 minutes. Occasionally I fall asleep for a couple of hours. Otherwise, I do nothing.
ghprop_problem_3: Weakening bladder control. Recently I have had problems with holding urine. I have always had a weak bladder, but this is definitely different.
ghprop_bother_3: I wear protection in public much more often than I used to. I recently had an accident while walking in a park.
ghprop_relieve_3: I try to remember to wear protection, and/or plan for it by knowing if public restrooms will be available where I am going
psprop_problem: Feeling overwhelmed. I am currently caring for my elderly mother in my home, and I feel like I can't keep up with all of the things that need to by done. I also feel very stressed because I do not want her to know I have Parkinsons. My father had it and it was hard on all of us, physically and emotionally. I don't want mom to have to relive that pain.
psprop_bother: I feel like I'm going through the motions rather than truly engaging.
psprop_relieve: I go to a monthly support group. I try to walk daily, outdoors when possible. I try to spend reminisce with mom about family stories.
pdprop_problem: The pain and discomfort in my right arm.
pdprop_bother: It sometimes makes getting work done difficult.
pdprop_relieve: Reposition my arm, rest it, stop working at whatever task I'm doing, wait until my next dose of Sinemet relieves it

ghprop_problem: Stiffness and pain in my right arm and hand, as well as dyskinysia in the hand itself
ghprop_bother: It impedes my use of my right hand, making routine tasks more of a struggle and/or more painful. Keyboarding is more of a struggle, cooking and cleaning and normal household  chores are more tedious. Getting my wallet out of my purse and opening it is slower and more tedious.  Drying my hair is more painful and tedious.
ghprop_relieve: My medication lessens the symptoms for parts of the day, so I try to do stuff during my ON times, but they are not always predictible. I have also used heat and cold to help relieve the pain in my hand. Pain relievers such as Advil do not help. Spray on pain relievers do not help either.
ghprop_problem_2: Urinary incontinence.
ghprop_bother_2: Very recently, (last week,this week), I started experiencing worsening urinary incontinence. I have always had a weak bladder, but suddenly I have nowhere near the control I used to have. I now have to wear a protective pad anytime I go out, and I'm wondering if I will soon need to switch that to a complete undergarment. Part of the problem stems, I believe, fromthe increased amount of water I am now drinking with my medication. Because my ON times have become shorter, I am now trying to maximize my medication's effectiveness. I am also trying to avoid protein for an hour before and after taking my Synemet.
ghprop_relieve_2: I'm going to try and start doing Kegal exercises.
ghprop_bother_3: I don't get as much done as I used to. I need to take more frequent breaks because I tire more easily. Some days I need to take long naps, but I try to avoid that as much as possible because it leaves me feeling down and disoriented.
ghprop_relieve_3: I have recently increased my exercise routine and I think that is helping.
psprop_problem: I can't do as much as I want to do. I can't cook as much as I want to, I can't work on my geneology as much as I want to, I can't keep up with correspondence as much as I want to. I would love to start new projects now that I am retire, but the time and energy just isn't there. I get frustrated because I know exercise and nutrition is so  important, but by the time I address them, there doesn't seem to be much time left for everything else.
psprop_bother: I don't get around to taking care of household chores and routine errands like I used to.
psprop_relieve: I'm trying to learn to let go and accept the new normal
psprop_problem_2: I expected to keep in more frequent contact with family members and friends after retiring, but Parkinson's makes it more of a struggle.
psprop_bother_2: It afftects my mood and threatens to increase my depression
psprop_relieve_2: Nothing
pdprop_problem: Pain, stiffness, rigidity, and dyskinesia in my right arm and hand.
pdprop_bother: It impedes my ability to do normal daily tasks with ease. The pain will discourage me from doing more sometimes.
pdprop_relieve: Heat and cold sometimes help. When the Synemet is working it definitely helps

ghprop_problem: Parkinson's. It affects many aspects of my daily life:. Tremor, slowness of movement, required gym routine, concern about the future.
ghprop_bother: The tremor is especially active when eating, which makes meal out with others somewhere between embarrassing and entertaining. Slowness of movement means people are up and out of the car before I've gotten the door open. I love going to the gym... but I might rather stay home! No one can tell me what the future holds, or when.
ghprop_relieve: I take meds, see my dr., and exercise. Talk to my therapist.
ghprop_problem_2: SVT and afib. I have both of these. They don't actually bother me but it might be pertinent to the study.
ghprop_bother_2: Occasional worry about stroke with afib.
ghprop_relieve_2: Take a pill for SVT. Gym probably helps.
ghprop_problem_3: Sleep and Sleep apnea. (severe) I love my cpap.
ghprop_bother_3: I have recently experienced more tiredness than usual. What might cause that? I get up in the morning, putter around for an hour or two, then go back to bed for an hour. My cpap report is good.
ghprop_relieve_3: CPAP and naps. I've asked doctors what might be causing this. No clear indicators. Have added B12 to meds
ghprop_problem_4: I'm overweight. A recent knee injury made it very clear that it would be good to lose a few points.
ghprop_bother_4: I feel heavy and weighty. I would like move faster and be more spry if I weighed less.
ghprop_relieve_4: I'm reducing my sugar and moderating my diet. Adding more cardio to my gym routine.
psprop_problem: As mentioned in the previous section my family is not comfortable initiating conversations about my PD. I am open to talking about my experience, but it is easier if someone asks a question.
psprop_bother: I feel a bit annoyed, sometimes sad and disappointed.
psprop_relieve: I talk to my therapist who points out that it is my responsibility to make my needs known.
psprop_problem_2: I resent having to be so fully present in my body in the moment.
psprop_bother_2: On alert to avoid falling. Aware of my tremor. Planning the next move. Trying to remember how I used to do something because what I'm doing now isn't working.
psprop_relieve_2: I try to be gentle with myself. I'm not in pain, not getting chemo... it could be worse.
psprop_problem_3: Occasionally my tremor fires  up in public in a way that is embarrassing.
psprop_bother_3: My functioning is not impacted. It can be alarming to see my body so out of control
pdprop_problem: My tremor. At different times it affects my hands, arms, legs and head. It seems to get especially fired up when there is stress or a lot of stimulation. Other times my body can be very still and quiet
pdprop_bother: It mostly affects eating, which I categorize as a high stimulation event. My right leg starts bouncing up and down, and my hands start to shake. Food often goes flying off a fork. Spoons work better. My effort to keep the food on a utensil slows the movement from the plate to my mouth. My head goes to meet it which results in some awkwardness getting the food in my mouth, which is facing down to the plate rather than holding my head vertically.
pdprop_relieve: I can often stop, close my eyes, and stop my leg from jumping and reduce my hand tremor. I switch from fork to spoon and routinely ask for a spoon at restaurants.. I also switch hands... often my left hand is steadier than my right.
pdprop_problem_2: Complex movements that involve motion flowing throughout the body. For instance, getting into and out of a car, and getting in and out of bed. My physical experience is that the "connectors" that pass the  movement from one body part to another have gotten lost. So, rather than flowing in one connected motion, I execute a series of discrete moves that are planned. The energy that comes from the flowing motion is not available in the step by step process.
pdprop_bother_2: The energy that comes from the flowing motion is not available in the step by step process. This results in everything taking a longer time and requiring more effort. For instance, in a car the other person is up and out of the car before I have turned and gotten by legs out. Beds are a special problem when traveling. Most beds are soft and I sink into the mattress. Trying to get positioned requires hoisting myself up and out of the "hole" in the mattress. This takes a lot of effort. I don't remember how I used to manage movement in bed.
pdprop_relieve_2: While this bothers me I generally manage to deal with it. If I focus I can speed up and ease the car movements. I bitch about soft beds.  Adjusting position and rolling over in bed is still a problem on my firm mattress, and I worry that at some point I will not be able to execute these movements.
pdprop_problem_3: Falling. Since I have been diagnosed (2015) I ave had several falls. They seem to come in spurts, and I have had long periods when I have not fallen. Except for minor scrapes and bruising I have not hurt myself.
pdprop_bother_3: Knowing that I'm at risk for falling makes me hyper alert. It is a nagging thought that is often at the forefront of my mind. The best that can be said about it is that I am here now. I don't trust my balance.
pdprop_relieve_3: I consciously scan the sidewalk / trail as I walk. I hold onto handrails. I am careful around curbs. I choose flat even ground to to walk on. I have trekking poles.
pdprop_problem_4: My family doesn't ask about my experience. While they have all indicated support, especially long-car financial help if necessary, they seem uninterested in my day to day experience
pdprop_bother_4: It makes me sad and disappointed
pdprop_relieve_4: I talk to my therapist who patiently tells me it is my responsibility to make my needs known. Sigh
pdprop_problem_5: Strangers often treat me as if I'm very old. Which is to say they are kind and helpful, even at times that I think I'm doing well.
pdprop_bother_5: It makes me wonder what they see that may be different from my self image.
pdprop_relieve_5: I'm grateful to realize there is a great deal of kindness in the world

ghprop_problem: the most bothersome problem is the hand tremors.
ghprop_bother: the tremors make it difficult to do some of the things I enjoy doing, like tinkering in my shop and doing artwork. I sometimes have trouble putting in a screw, keeping my brush hand steady, holding a camera steady etc. Trying to work say all day if I signup for a n art workshop has become more difficult because as I become more tired the tremors become more prornonced.  typing and writing by hand are also a problem at times.
ghprop_relieve: I avoid  trying to sketch out side  some where aand workfor the most part in my studio where I can use a table or some thing to brace or steady my hand.  If I,m in an art  workshop I try to rest occasionally so I dont get so tired.  Screws, nuts etc. remain a challege at times.
ghprop_problem_2: I have been having a problem with low blood pressure.  usually it is in the morning  or at Rock Steady boxing if we have just done something particulary strenuous.
ghprop_bother_2: I dont want to pass-out, fall and hurt myself.
ghprop_relieve_2: I was perscribed a medication to raise my blod preasure but only took twice.  Pressure in my head in the morning and frquent need to pee at nite. So now at my neurologists suggestion I try to stay well hydrated and add extra salt to my food.
ghprop_problem_3: This should be my # 2 problem. My mental abilities are deteriating.  My spelling, math and memory are getting worse.
ghprop_bother_3: I find it harder to remember who the characters  are when I read a novel.  measuring and working with fractions when I do say woodworking or cut a picture mat has become more difficult.I  often have to ask my wife what we are doing or where we are going multiple times                                                                  in a da  in a
ghprop_relieve_3: I need to take extra care with things like measuring etc.   My wife and I keep a calender and I check it on a daily basis. I try tokeep a charater list in my head when I read I should probibly writte it down.
ghprop_problem_4: Difficulty sleeping. Getting to, staying and waking up early.  I often wake-up needing to go to the bathroom (i,ve got BPH) and then lay there getting increasingly uncomfortable.
ghprop_bother_4: A lack of sleep makes my other PD problems worse.
ghprop_relieve_4: I try to keep to a schedule.  I don't look at the clock when I wake-up during the nite.  Don,t turn on lights when I do go to the bathroom.  The last month or so I have 1 of my carbadopa/ Levidopa that I take and that often seems to enable me to sleep.
ghprop_problem_5: I feel spacy or disoriented in places like crowds or stores.
ghprop_bother_5: It makes being in a crowd or shopping an uncomfortable experience.
psprop_problem: I would like to have a closer friendship(s) with someone or a group of people with commom interests. Outside of my imediate family ( wife and son I don't have any family nearby, neighbors that are good friends and a limited social circle of people that I really feel close to. My best friend of many years is in a nursing home with dementia and  several other friends have died.
psprop_bother: It doesn't really bother my daily functioning. Guess I just have this idealized image in my head of a group of people or even one person    working and socializing together, in my area of interest , which is the visual arts.
psprop_relieve: I have become friendly with one of the guys in my RockSteady boxing group.  we have good conversations going back and forth from boxing.  He does,t share my interest in the arts but we both have many other things we like to talk about then and occasionally we will go to lunch together.  I am also fortunate that I have a wife who also shares my interest in the arts and is a very intellegent woman.

ghprop_problem: Standing and walking gives me severe back pain. This pain radiates from my middle back down to my left leg hamstrings. I have difficulty shifting position in bed at night with hamstring pain. This can interrupt my sleep, leading to daytime fatigue.
ghprop_bother: I can't walk 1 mile. I used to run and ski cross country, so I find this to be very frustrating. I have back pain and a short, marching gait. If I am washing dishes or vacuuming, I have to rest frequently as a break from the pain. I have great difficulty using a walk-behind lawnmower.
ghprop_relieve: I have been doing physical therapy for leg and back pain. Twice, I have had nerve ablation on L4 L5 vertebrae. This has given me partial relief. I also have a 1.5 hour massage about once per 2 months. I have had some results previously seeing a chiropractor.
ghprop_problem_2: Slurred, muffled speaking voice. Wife, friends, and associates often ask me to repeat myself. I have also listened to my voice on video and it can be quiet and partially unintelligable.
ghprop_bother_2: My wife gets frustrated and scolds me. This can be upsetting to both of us and negatively impacts our relationship.  I often feel I am communicating clearly, only to get feedback to the contrary.
ghprop_relieve_2: I try to speak loudly and with intent. Often this is not sufficient and I have to repeat myself. I took the Lee Silverman voice therapy with good results. I am now enrolled in Connecting Voices, a singing group for PD. It is a fun class, but not as effective as one on one therapy.
ghprop_problem_3: Daytime fatigue. I am tired a lot of the time leading to difficulty completing tasks. I frequently need a nap for 45 minutes to 2.5 hours.
ghprop_bother_3: I sometimes have difficulty concentrating and completing lengthy tasks. I typically take naps, sometimes twice per day. If I don't nap, I feel tired and distracted.
ghprop_relieve_3: As described, take naps. My wife is very understanding of my need for rest.
ghprop_problem_4: Difficulty getting a good night's sleep. This contributes to daytime fatigue. I use a CPAP for sleep apnea. I talk in my sleep and occasionally flail arms or kick with legs. My left hamstring can be very sore resulting in difficulty getting comfortable.
ghprop_bother_4: I am often sleepy as described above. This makes social activities and interactions with friends and family less enjoyable as well as contributing to difficulty completing tasks as described previously.
ghprop_relieve_4: I use a CPAP to counteract sleep apnea. We bought a new mattress and pillows. My wife nudges me if I talk or act out in my sleep. We try to maintain a regular sleep schedule. I nap when I can. I tried melatonin but didn't like how I felt in the morning.
ghprop_problem_5: I experience stiffness, and loss of dexterity due to Parkinson's Disease. I have some difficult typing, using the computer mouse, and performing tasks requiring fine motor skills.
ghprop_bother_5: I sometimes lock up and can't  complete important tasks. I have been told I can't ski anymore.
ghprop_relieve_5: DBS and carbidopa-levadopa plus requip help. I take periodic breaks and stretch. I have had good results with physical therapy.
psprop_problem: We don't get out much. I am not motivated to go out to the gym, dance, take day trips, play golf, bowl, sail, hike, bike, cross-country ski, or other physical activities of which I am capable. We don't socialize or date much, and end up spending most of our evenings watching TV. We do go out during the day to restaurants a lot.
psprop_bother: Unfortunately, this doesn't bother me enough so I get motivated to do something about it. My wife definitely would like to get out more. It is making our relationship dull or stale. It is easy to get into a comfortable rut. My physical and health issues limit me but don't force me to cease activities.
psprop_relieve: Clearly the problems don't motivate me enough to do something about it. We need to prioritize this, make a plan and stick to the plan. I also need to derive fun from activities I used to enjoy. Finding active things we both enjoy is important.
psprop_problem_2: I don't see much of family and friends. After my divorce, there is some awkwardness with family and friends get-togethers. Some people are closer to my ex-wife. My family sees more of my ex-wife due to family traditions. My wife has not been shown the love by my sons.
psprop_bother_2: Again, this is not an urgent problem. It comes up only when there are scheduled activities such as my son's performances, birthdays, and holidays.
psprop_relieve_2: We are trying to set our own traditions by planning and hosting family get-togethers.  This can be a fair amount of work to prepare, especially for my wife. We also try to attend my son's performances. Some of the awkwardness is going away, though there is a long way to go. We also have a couple friends we see periodically.
psprop_problem_3: Downsizing, we are attempting to get rid of stuff that accumulated from consolidating multiple households. This will lighten our load and make it easier to manage the house and our eventual estate by our heirs.
psprop_bother_3: My wife is more concerned about this than I am. I am relatively content with the state of the house. She does tend to shop frequently, often adding the latest bargains to an already full house. This can be frustrating. I need to get rid of my parents' souveniers, old electronics, books and DVDs.
psprop_relieve_3: Periodically, I get motivated to clean up, such as when preparing for company. I need to schedule time to make a more significant dent in the remaining items.
psprop_problem_4: I don't help out with household chores as much as I should. Often chores like vacuuming or doing dishes lead to fatigue or back pain. I also don't help a lot with yardwork.
psprop_bother_4: My wife does a larger portion of the chores, leading to frustration on her part. Periodically this leads to marital squabbles.
psprop_relieve_4: I try to do more and work through the pain. Physical therapy helps me to be more flexible.
psprop_problem_5: I tend to be somewhat self-absorbed and don't give my wife emotional support. I don't always recognise opportunities to be supportive or how to respond appropriately.
psprop_bother_5: My wife gets angry at me and scolds me. I feel somewhat blind-sided as my perception is that things are going well.
psprop_relieve_5: I am trying to look for opportunities to be more supportive of my wife's emotional needs. I am trying to better feel empathy for her situation and respond in ways that don't add fuel to the fire.
pdprop_problem: Unsteady marching walking gait.
pdprop_bother: Difficulty walking n a variety of surfaces. Inability to walk reasonable distances. Back pain associated with walking or standing.
pdprop_relieve: Physical therapy to increase core strength and reduce back pain. I don't work directly on gait with PT. I have tried to have DBS adjusted without success due to side effects. I THINK I ALREADY ANSWERED 2 to 5!

ghprop_problem: Orthopedic problems such as sore knees and back-pain. Problems related to Parkinson's Disease such as shuffling gait and inability to walk medium to long distances.
ghprop_bother: Orthopedic problems cause pain when washing dishes, vacuuming, or walking around the block. Shuffling gait contribute to the inability to walk around the block or in supermarket.
ghprop_relieve: I have participated in Physical Therapy and a home exercise program. Exercises have addressed knee and back strength and flexibility. PT also addresses gait problems with walking practice. I am also riding stationery reclined bike and walking to increase endurance. I have had nerve ablation to lessen back pain. I am consulting with a surgeon about knee replacement.
ghprop_problem_2: Daytime fatigue. I get tired during the day, and feel unmotivated. This seems tied to dosage of PD medication such as Ropinirole CR. I have tried reducing the dosage, but have had some degradation of PD symptoms.
ghprop_bother_2: I am routinely tired at lest twice per day. If I am at home, I nap. If I am on the road, I meditate.
ghprop_relieve_2: I regularly take naps, sometimes in the morning and afternoon to compensate for listlessness and brain fog. I am adjusting my medication to try and reduce source of fatigue.
ghprop_problem_3: Stiffness and lack of flexibility due to PD.
ghprop_bother_3: Lack of flexibility can make typing on the computer slow and painstaking. I sometimes freeze when typing or moving the mouse.
ghprop_relieve_3: I shake out muscles and stretch periodically.
ghprop_problem_4: Soft or slurred talking voice - difficulty talking on the phone or face to face. Many times, I feel that I am speaking clearly but receive feedback that I am not.
ghprop_bother_4: It is frustrating to me to try and communicate, only to be told it is not good enough. My wife, my primary communications partner is often frustrated and asks me to repeat myself.
ghprop_relieve_4: I try to speak with more intent and volume. I try to respond to feedback from my wife and others by adjusting my speech. I have taken speech therapy in the past and am considering it for the near future.
ghprop_problem_5: I have some problems operating an automobile. There are times when I don't pay full attention to my driving and have unsafe practices such as excess speed, cutting off another driver or drifting out of my lane.
ghprop_bother_5: I am startled when I do something unsafe. Many times I don't notice the unsafe practice(s). My wife calls the practice(s) to my attention.
ghprop_relieve_5: I am paying more attention while driving. I am monitoring and adjusting my speed. I look both ways when maneuvering in parking lots.
psprop_problem: Personal: I have eliminated or have difficulty performing activities that I previously had significant expertise.
psprop_bother: I no longer ski because of concerns about hurting myself or my Deep Brain Stimulator (DBS). I have difficulty sailing due to lack of strength and balance issues.
psprop_relieve: I am increasing strength and balance through my home exercise program. I am sailing with a little help from friends.
psprop_problem_2: Family: I don't see or talk to my three sons much.
psprop_bother_2: I miss talking to my children and grandchildren.
psprop_relieve_2: I am trying to more routinely call my sons. We are also setting up zoom meetings such as game night.
psprop_problem_3: Social: I don't keep in touch with friends.
psprop_bother_3: I miss the social interaction. I used to play golf. I enjoyed the sport and socializing.
psprop_relieve_3: Not much. This doesn't bother me enough for me to do much. I do keep in touch with my sailing buddy.
psprop_problem_4: Personal / Financial: I feel I have more capacity to consult with manufacturing management clients. I have difficulty motivating to market my services.
psprop_bother_4: I am a capable consultant and that I could earn money while helping others.  I was able to do two successful projects in recent years. The cash flow was helpful but my Social Security benefit was reduced. As I am over 66 years old, I now am not limited on my earnings.
psprop_relieve_4: Not much - I am getting used to retirement.
psprop_problem_5: Personal: I don't help out with house and yard work as much as I should.
psprop_bother_5: Decluttering and cleaning tasks are slipping. Yard work is getting out of hand. My wife picks up much of the slack. I should be able to contribute more time and effort.
psprop_relieve_5: I am trying to do more. I routinely do the dishes. I mow the lawn and do some yard work. I have done some organization of basement and closet.
pdprop_problem: Gait problems. I have shuffling gait, short strides and difficulty stopping when my speed gets a little out of control. Occasionally I freeze when starting to walk.
pdprop_bother: The shuffling gait makes it difficult to walk medium to long distances. Shopping is difficult. Walking in my neighborhood is limited and hiking, which I used to enjoy, is out of the question.
pdprop_relieve: I am routinely doing my home exercise program as set up by my physical therapist. Every other day, I do 20 minutes on the stationary bike. I am walking increased distances with better strides. If I freeze, I start marching to restart. By adding Levodopa / Carbidopa in the morning, my gait and other PD symptoms have improved.
pdprop_problem_2: Lack of flexibility when performing manual tasks. Sometimes, I lock up when typing or operating the mouse on the computer.
pdprop_bother_2: It can be frustrating when I am trying to accomplish a task and I stall.

ghprop_problem: Parkinson's Disease walking limitations, balance problems, and sleep difficulties.
ghprop_bother: Walking limitations make it difficult to get around and participate in fun activities. Balance problems have resulted in falls and fear of falling. Sleep difficulties result in rough nights and daytime fatigue.
ghprop_relieve: I use a rollator to help with walking and balance. I am following an exercise program with inconsistency to help with walking and repositioning in bed. I use a CPAP and urinals by the bed at night. I try to limit evening drinking. I am going for a study for a Medtronics device to help with Over Active Bladder,
ghprop_problem_2: Heart AFIB - Atrial Fibulation. I am overweight, obese, which contributes to AFIB, and Sleep Apnea. Other than that, I feel I am in good health. I could lose 50 pounds.
ghprop_bother_2: It contributes to balance problems, and fatigue. Ultimately, heart problems could result in my death.
ghprop_relieve_2: Exercise should help this. I also take a daily pill to mediate AFIB and another to control cholesterol.
ghprop_problem_3: Movement difficulties and tremor due to Parkinson's Disease.
ghprop_bother_3: Writing is cramped and illegible. Hand tasks, such as typing, are slower. Voice is somewhat slurred and mumbled.
ghprop_relieve_3: A combination of medication and Medtronics Deep Brain Stimulation control tremors and help with other PD symptoms. I have had voice therapy and participate in Loud Crowd for voice maintenance - Speaking with Intent.
ghprop_problem_4: Orthopedic issues such as stiff back and knee pain.
ghprop_bother_4: Pain limits walking and make household tasks difficult.
ghprop_relieve_4: Home exercise program helps increase strength and flexibility. Steroid injections in knees and back reduce pain. I have knee injections every three months, and fairly routine back injections.
ghprop_problem_5: Depression and Anxiety can be frustrating.
ghprop_bother_5: I have lost confidence in my ability to perform my career job responsibilities. I tend to dislike and avoid social activities and travel.
ghprop_relieve_5: My wife gives me regular encouragement. I try to maintain a positive outlook.
psprop_problem: Social activities are limited.
psprop_bother: I have lost physical capabilities that I previously could perform well. This has resulted in my limiting activities such as camping, golf, and sailing. I either avoid those activities or friends don't ask me to participate.
psprop_relieve: I try not to get discouraged. I ask for help from family and friends while trying not to be a burden on others.  Exercise and practice of specific skills help build confidence.
psprop_problem_2: I have limited contact with my sons and their families.
psprop_bother_2: I miss interacting with my sons, their wives, and grandchildren. We have minimal interaction by phone and in person. Prior to my divorce, we had regular family get-togethers such as family camp and Sunday dinners.
psprop_relieve_2: I try to more routinely call my sons. I show interest in what is going on in their lives. We have worked to develop other activities to build memories.
psprop_problem_3: I have difficulty keeping up with house and yard work. My wife takes on more than her fair share of home maintenance tasks.
psprop_bother_3: More tasks performed by my wife leads to an inequitable split of duties. She gets frustrated and she scolds me. This results in a strained relationship.
psprop_relieve_3: I try to help out more and complete my own projects. I endeavor to achieve a more equitable division of workload.  Happy wife, happy life. We are considering downsizing to a smaller home, possibly a condo. with grounds maintenance included.
psprop_problem_4: Personal hygiene and grooming needs to be more consistent.
psprop_bother_4: It doesn't bother me sufficiently for me to pay it enough attention. When my wife points out problems or oversights, I address them.
psprop_relieve_4: I try to pay more attention to grooming tasks and results. I try to remember to look in the mirror. I keep facial cream in the car console.
psprop_problem_5: Lack of motivation to do exercises.
psprop_relieve_5: I am trying to get more routine with my home-based physical therapy. My new walker makes walking in the neighborhood more practical.
pdprop_problem: Walking and gait issues. I have great difficulty walking, a skill that used to be second-nature.
pdprop_bother: I use a walker to get around, in the house and when out and about. I have problems participating in activities I used to enjoy such as hiking, walking on the beach, launching a sailboat, and romantic walks.
pdprop_relieve: I take 50 mg of Carbidopa Levodopa every 2.5 hours during the day as well as 400 mg of CL sustained release morning and noon. I also take 6 mg of Ropinirole each morning. I use the walker more frequently to walk in the neighborhood for exercise.
pdprop_problem_2: Falling and fear of falling due to balance issues. Frequency and severity have increased  lately.
pdprop_bother_2: Falling has resulted in some painful episodes. Luckily, I have yet to break a bone.
pdprop_relieve_2: I constantly have to remain vigilant while doing house and yard work. I watch out for and try to eliminate trip hazards. I use a rollator to steady myself.
pdprop_problem_3: Daytime fatigue due to difficulty getting a good night sleep. I find it hard to get comfortable and to shift position in bed. This is compounded by the urge to urinate frequently. I also have sleep apnea and have to use a CPAP.
pdprop_bother_3: Fatigue limits my motivation to complete tasks. I require a 30 to  90 minute nap each day. I don't enjoy  sleeping and somewhat dread going to bed.
pdprop_relieve_3: We replaced our bed and some of the linens. I got help from my Physical Therapist on ways to maneuver in bed. I take Myrbetriq to reduce the urge to urinate and will be testing a bladder stimulator to help to reduce frequency of urination. I try to drink mostly before 4 pm.
pdprop_problem_4: Voice problems include muffled speech and some slurring of words. I often have to repeat myself.
pdprop_bother_4: It can be very frustrating to have to repeat myself constantly. My wife gets angry with me, resulting in a strained relationship.
pdprop_relieve_4: I have participated in speech therapy. I also attend weekly, the Loud Crowd, for a coached group effort to sustain Speaking with Intent.
pdprop_problem_5: Cramped, illegible handwriting and difficulty with manual tasks such as typing.
pdprop_bother_5: I can't read my own writing. I have difficulty keeping up with typing needs. Tasks requiring fine motor skills are tedious.
pdprop_relieve_5: I type most of my written communications. Deep Brain Stimulation helps with manual tasks and has almost eliminated resting tremor.

adverse_1: Participant was seen on 4/26/2021 in clinic for their baseline visit where they were set up on the MC10 sensors for the first time. On 4/27/2021 the participant contacted study coordinator Julia Soto about the sensors not connected to the dock. Julia was able to help with no re-application of the sensors being necessary. Then on 4/28/2021 the participant contacted Julia again due to sensors not being ready. One of the sensors was failing so a new sensor was provisioned. On May 1st, 2021 the participant contacted Julia again because they were not able to pass the cardio check after multiple attempts. After these multiple attempt the participant reported a red, itchy, mildly painful rash around the entire area where the sensors had been worn. Proper application and removal methods were explained and used according to the participant. The participant opted to stop wearing the sensors on Saturday May 1st due to the skin irritation, thus stopping their burst 2 days early and completing 5/7 days. At this time they do not wish to withdraw as they are confident it was re-applying them so many times that caused this irritation  and they are willing to try again in the future. The rash cleared up on 5/12/2021.
